<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ws-dot-product.ptx
    Worksheet 1.3: The Dot Product.

    Ports the original 01_02_Dot_Product.tex slide deck.  Same board
    organization as the Beamer notes:
        I.   Definition (geometric and component forms)
        II.  Geometric interpretation, angle, and orthogonality
        III. Projections (enrichment growing out of the "component
             of a along b" line in the deck)
        IV.  Properties of the dot product and the basic inequalities
        V.   Application: work done by a constant force

    Guided-notes pattern (see ws-function-notation.ptx for the full
    explanation):
        - <fillin characters="N"/> (or \fillin[N] inside math) draws a
          blank in every build.
        - The intended answer follows in a <commentary> block.  As in
          ws-vectors.ptx and ws-function-notation.ptx, those blocks are
          kept COMMENTED OUT for now: the project currently has no
          target that turns the 'commentary' stringparam on (see the
          'can't-use-commentary' history), so an uncommented block would
          stay hidden in every build anyway.  They are preserved in the
          source, in order, ready to switch on once a key target sets
          commentary="yes".
        - Multi-step worked computations are <exercise>s with a
          <solution> body, whose visibility is controlled by the
          publication file's <exercise-worksheet @solution="..."/>.

    Figures (the geometric-interpretation picture and the wagon/work
    diagram) are left as <figure> placeholders so the original
    9_2_Fig5 / 9_2_Fig6 / 9_2_Fig10 PNGs can be dropped in later.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-dot-product">
    <title>The Dot Product</title>

    <objectives>
        <ul>
            <li>Compute the dot product of two vectors two different
                ways and recognize that the result is a scalar.</li>
            <li>Use <m>\va \cdot \vb = \norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}\cos\theta</m>
                to find the angle between vectors and to test for
                orthogonality.</li>
            <li>Compute scalar and vector projections of one vector
                onto another.</li>
            <li>State and use the algebraic properties of the dot
                product and the triangle and Cauchy&#8211;Schwarz
                inequalities.</li>
            <li>Apply the dot product to compute the work done by a
                constant force.</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 1: Definition (geometric and component forms)
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>I. Definition.</alert>
            (Vector Operation #2)</p>

        <p>
            The <term>dot product</term> is our first way to
            <em>multiply</em> two vectors.  Unlike vector addition, it
            combines two vectors into a single number.  Let
            <m>\va = [a_1, a_2, a_3]</m> and
            <m>\vb = [b_1, b_2, b_3]</m>.  Geometrically, the dot
            product is
            <me>
                \va \cdot \vb = \fillin[18]
            </me>
            where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\va</m> and
            <m>\vb</m>.  An easier way to compute the dot product of two
            known vectors is to use components:
            <me>
                \va \cdot \vb
                = [a_1, a_2, a_3] \cdot [b_1, b_2, b_3]
                = \fillin[28]
            </me>
        </p>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order:
                <m>\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}\cos\theta</m> and
                <m>a_1 b_1 + a_2 b_2 + a_3 b_3</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary> -->

        <p>
            <alert>Note.</alert>
            Both formulas produce the same single real number, so for
            <m>\va, \vb \in \R^3</m> the dot product
            <m>\va \cdot \vb \in</m> <fillin characters="6"/>
            <nbsp/>&#8212; a <fillin characters="8"/>, never a vector.
            (For this reason the dot product is also called the
            <term>scalar product</term>.)
        </p>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>Blanks, in order: <m>\R</m>, and <q>scalar</q>.</p>
        </commentary> -->

        <exercise xml:id="ex-dp-compute">
            <title>Computing a dot product</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compute <m>\va \cdot \vb</m> for
                    <m>\va = [1, 2, 3]</m> and
                    <m>\vb = [-2, 0, 5]</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Using the component formula,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \va \cdot \vb
                            \amp = (1)(-2) + (2)(0) + (3)(5) </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = -2 + 0 + 15 = 13.          </mrow>
                    </md>
                    The answer is a single number, as it must be.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-dp-compute">
            <title>Dot-product practice</title>
            <task xml:id="task-dp-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        With <m>\va = [3, -1, 2]</m> and
                        <m>\vb = [4, 5, 1]</m>, compute
                        <m>\va \cdot \vb</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\va \cdot \vb = (3)(4) + (-1)(5) + (2)(1)
                        = 12 - 5 + 2 = 9</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-dp-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        With <m>\vu = 2\vi - \vj + 3\vk</m> and
                        <m>\vv = \vi + 4\vj - \vk</m>, compute
                        <m>\vu \cdot \vv</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\vu \cdot \vv = (2)(1) + (-1)(4) + (3)(-1)
                        = 2 - 4 - 3 = -5</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 2: Geometric interpretation, angle, orthogonality
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>II. Geometric interpretation.</alert></p>

        <p>
            Solving the geometric formula for <m>\cos\theta</m> turns
            the dot product into an angle-measuring tool:
            <me>
                \cos\theta = \fillin[22]
            </me>
            Because <m>\norm{\va}</m> and <m>\norm{\vb}</m> are
            positive, the <em>sign</em> of <m>\va \cdot \vb</m> alone
            already tells you the kind of angle: a positive dot product
            means an <fillin characters="6"/> <nbsp/>angle, a negative
            one means an <fillin characters="7"/> <nbsp/>angle, and a
            zero dot product means a <fillin characters="5"/>
            <nbsp/>angle.
        </p>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order:
                <m>\dfrac{\va \cdot \vb}{\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}}</m>;
                <q>acute</q>, <q>obtuse</q>, <q>right</q>.
            </p>
        </commentary> -->

        <figure xml:id="fig-dp-interpretation">
            <caption>The dot product as
                <m>(\text{component of } \va \text{ along } \vb)
                \times (\text{length of } \vb)</m>.</caption>
            <!-- TODO: drop in the original 9_2_Fig5.png, e.g.
                 <image source="figures/dot-product-projection.png"
                        width="50%"/>
                 or replace with an inline TikZ <latex-image>. -->
            <image>
                <description>Two vectors a and b drawn from a common
                    point with angle theta between them.  A
                    perpendicular dropped from the tip of a onto the
                    line through b marks off the segment of length
                    |a| cos(theta), the component of a along b.</description>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
            That last case is important enough to record as a theorem.
        </p>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-orthogonal">
            <title>Orthogonality test</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m> be nonzero vectors.
                    Then <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m> are
                    <term>orthogonal</term> (perpendicular) if and only
                    if <m>\va \cdot \vb = <fillin characters="2"/></m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>Fill in: <m>0</m>.</p>
        </commentary> -->

        <exercise xml:id="ex-dp-angle">
            <title>The angle between two vectors</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the angle between <m>\va = [1, 0, 1]</m> and
                    <m>\vb = [0, 1, 1]</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \cos\theta
                            \amp = \frac{\va \cdot \vb}
                                        {\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}}
                                 = \frac{0 + 0 + 1}
                                        {\sqrt{2}\,\sqrt{2}}    </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = \frac{1}{2}.                  </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So <m>\theta = \dfrac{\pi}{3}</m>; the vectors are
                    sixty degrees apart.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-dp-ortho">
            <title>Testing for orthogonality</title>
            <task xml:id="task-ortho-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Are <m>\va = [1, 2, -1]</m> and
                        <m>\vb = [3, -1, 1]</m> orthogonal?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\va \cdot \vb = 3 - 2 - 1 = 0</m>, so yes
                        &#8212; the two vectors meet at a right angle.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-ortho-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find a value of <m>c</m> for which
                        <m>[2, c, -3]</m> and <m>[4, 1, c]</m> are
                        orthogonal.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Set the dot product to zero:
                        <m>8 + c - 3c = 0</m>, i.e.
                        <m>8 - 2c = 0</m>, so <m>c = 4</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 3: Projections (enrichment)
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>III. Projections.</alert></p>

        <p>
            The geometric picture above measures <q>how much</q> of one
            vector points along another &#8212; the length of the shadow
            <m>\va</m> casts on the line through <m>\vb</m>.  That length
            is the <term>scalar projection</term> of <m>\va</m> onto
            <m>\vb</m>,
            <me>
                \comp_{\vb} \va = \norm{\va}\cos\theta = \fillin[16]
            </me>
            and stretching the unit vector
            <m>\vb / \norm{\vb}</m> to that length gives the
            <term>vector projection</term> of <m>\va</m> onto
            <m>\vb</m>,
            <me>
                \proj_{\vb} \va = \fillin[22]
            </me>
        </p>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order:
                <m>\dfrac{\va \cdot \vb}{\norm{\vb}}</m> and
                <m>\left(\dfrac{\va \cdot \vb}{\norm{\vb}^2}\right)\vb</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary> -->

        <exercise xml:id="ex-dp-proj">
            <title>A projection</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find <m>\comp_{\vb}\va</m> and
                    <m>\proj_{\vb}\va</m> for <m>\va = [3, 4, 0]</m>
                    and <m>\vb = [2, 0, 0]</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Here <m>\va \cdot \vb = 6</m> and
                    <m>\norm{\vb} = 2</m>, so
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \comp_{\vb}\va \amp = \frac{6}{2} = 3, </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \proj_{\vb}\va
                            \amp = \frac{6}{4}\,[2, 0, 0]
                                 = [3, 0, 0].                      </mrow>
                    </md>
                    The shadow of <m>\va</m> on the <m>x</m>-axis has
                    length <m>3</m>, exactly the first component of
                    <m>\va</m> &#8212; as expected, since <m>\vb</m>
                    points along the <m>x</m>-axis.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 4: Properties and inequalities
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>IV. Properties of the dot product.</alert></p>

        <p>
            Let <m>\va, \vb, \vc \in \R^3</m> and let <m>k</m> be a
            scalar.  Fill in the blanks.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Length: <m>\va \cdot \va = <fillin characters="8"/></m>,
                equivalently <m>\norm{\va} = <fillin characters="10"/></m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Commutative:
                <m>\va \cdot \vb = <fillin characters="8"/></m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Distributive:
                <m>(\va + \vb) \cdot \vc = <fillin characters="16"/></m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Scalars factor out:
                <m>k(\va \cdot \vb) = (k\va) \cdot \vb
                = \va \cdot (k\vb)</m>.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order:
                <m>\norm{\va}^2</m>; <m>\sqrt{\va \cdot \va}</m>;
                <m>\vb \cdot \va</m>;
                <m>\va \cdot \vc + \vb \cdot \vc</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary> -->

        <p>
            The very first property, <m>\va \cdot \va = \norm{\va}^2</m>,
            is the same length idea from the previous worksheet written
            in dot-product language &#8212; it is the bridge between the
            two formulas for <m>\va \cdot \vb</m>.
        </p>

        <p><alert>Two important inequalities.</alert></p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Triangle inequality:
                <m>\norm{\va + \vb} \le <fillin characters="16"/></m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Cauchy&#8211;Schwarz inequality:
                <m>\norm{\va \cdot \vb} \le <fillin characters="14"/></m>.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order:
                <m>\norm{\va} + \norm{\vb}</m> and
                <m>\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary> -->

        <p>
            Cauchy&#8211;Schwarz is exactly the statement that
            <m>\cos\theta = \dfrac{\va \cdot \vb}
            {\norm{\va}\,\norm{\vb}}</m> never leaves the interval
            <m>[-1, 1]</m> &#8212; so the angle formula always makes
            sense.
        </p>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 5: Application - work done by a constant force
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>V. Application: work.</alert></p>

        <p>
            In its most basic, one-dimensional form, the
            <term>work</term> done on an object is
            <me>
                \text{Work} = (\text{force on the object})
                \times (\text{distance moved}).
            </me>
            This simple product assumes two things:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>the force is <fillin characters="10"/>
                <nbsp/>(it does not change as the object moves), and</li>
            <li>the force acts in the
                <fillin characters="14"/> <nbsp/>direction as the
                motion.</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>Blanks, in order: <q>constant</q>, <q>same</q>.</p>
        </commentary> -->

        <p>
            Now let <m>\vF</m> be a constant force pulling a wagon and
            <m>\vr</m> the displacement of the wagon.  In general the
            force is <em>not</em> aligned with the motion, so we must
            decompose <m>\vF</m> to find how much of it actually acts
            along the displacement.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-dp-work">
            <caption>A force <m>\vF</m> applied at an angle
                <m>\theta</m> to the displacement <m>\vr</m> of a
                wagon.</caption>
            <!-- TODO: drop in the original 9_2_Fig6.png / 9_2_Fig10.png,
                 e.g. <image source="figures/work-wagon.png" width="55%"/>
                 or replace with an inline TikZ <latex-image>. -->
            <image>
                <description>A wagon on the ground pulled by a force F
                    directed up and to the right at angle theta above
                    the horizontal displacement r.  The horizontal
                    component |F| cos(theta) is the part of the force
                    doing work.</description>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
            The component of the force in the direction of motion is
            <m>\norm{\vF}\cos\theta</m>, and the distance travelled is
            <m>\norm{\vr}</m>.  Multiplying and recognizing the
            geometric form of the dot product,
            <me>
                \text{Work}
                = (\norm{\vF}\cos\theta)(\norm{\vr})
                = \norm{\vF}\,\norm{\vr}\cos\theta
                = \fillin[10]
            </me>
            So for any constant force, work is simply a dot product.
        </p>
        <!-- <commentary>
            <p>Fill in: <m>\vF \cdot \vr</m>.</p>
        </commentary> -->

        <exercise xml:id="ex-dp-work">
            <title>Work done on a wagon</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A wagon is pulled by a constant force
                    <m>\vF = [-5, 10]</m> newtons while its
                    displacement is <m>\vr = [-4, 0]</m> metres.  How
                    much work is done on the wagon?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \text{Work} = \vF \cdot \vr
                            \amp = [-5, 10] \cdot [-4, 0]      </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = (-5)(-4) + (10)(0)          </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = 20 \text{ N}\cdot\text{m}.  </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Only the horizontal part of the force does work
                    here, since the displacement is purely horizontal.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-dp-work">
            <title>Work practice</title>
            <task xml:id="task-work-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A constant force <m>\vF = [3, 4]</m> newtons
                        moves an object along the displacement
                        <m>\vr = [10, 0]</m> metres.  Find the work
                        done.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Work} = \vF \cdot \vr
                        = (3)(10) + (4)(0) = 30</m> N<m>\cdot</m>m.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-work-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A force of magnitude <m>50</m> N is applied at
                        <m>60^\circ</m> above the horizontal to drag a
                        crate <m>8</m> m horizontally.  Find the work
                        done.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Using
                        <m>\text{Work} = \norm{\vF}\,\norm{\vr}\cos\theta
                        = (50)(8)\cos 60^\circ = (400)\!\left(\tfrac12\right)
                        = 200</m> N<m>\cdot</m>m.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>

        <p>
            <alert>Looking ahead.</alert>
            The dot product multiplies two vectors to produce a
            <em>scalar</em>, and we have seen it measure lengths,
            angles, orthogonality, and work.  The next worksheet
            introduces the <term>cross product</term>, a second way to
            multiply two vectors &#8212; this time producing a
            <em>vector</em> perpendicular to both.
        </p>
    </page>

</worksheet>
